  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0512/Could-climate-change-shrink-Arctic-shorebirds">
    <title>Could climate change shrink Arctic shorebirds?</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0512/Could-climate-change-shrink-Arctic-shorebirds</link>
    <description><p>Rapid warming in the high Arctic may be fueling rapid evolution of red knots, according to new research.&nbsp;</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/nW1qgE7ScZA" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0512/Missing-mitochondria-Strange-eukaryotic-cell-lacks-powerhouse">
    <title>Missing mitochondria: Strange eukaryotic cell lacks 'powerhouse'</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0512/Missing-mitochondria-Strange-eukaryotic-cell-lacks-powerhouse</link>
    <description><p>Scientists have identified a living eukaryote that lacks mitochondria, thought essential for that type of cell to function.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/dxZ8DShzUO0" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0512/Could-ancient-space-dust-reveal-mysteries-of-Earth-s-early-atmosphere">
    <title>Could ancient space dust reveal mysteries of Earth's early atmosphere?</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0512/Could-ancient-space-dust-reveal-mysteries-of-Earth-s-early-atmosphere</link>
    <description><p>A new paper challenges the widely held belief that there was little to no oxygen in Earth's atmosphere 2.7 billion years ago.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/VuP4Tv6x30U" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0512/Unusual-heat-waves-in-Africa-will-soon-be-the-norm-study-says">
    <title>Unusual heat waves in Africa will soon be the norm, study says</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0512/Unusual-heat-waves-in-Africa-will-soon-be-the-norm-study-says</link>
    <description><p>By the end of the century, heat waves in Africa will be longer, hotter, and more frequent, say a team of researchers from Norway and Italy.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/FyI3NVANBNk" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0512/Damsels-in-distress-Coral-reef-decline-denudes-damselfish-of-defenses">
    <title>Damsels in distress: Coral reef decline denudes damselfish of defenses</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0512/Damsels-in-distress-Coral-reef-decline-denudes-damselfish-of-defenses</link>
    <description><p>A study shows that one of damselfish's key abilities, chemical cues to identify predators, is incapacitated when the coral at the core of its ecosystem perishes.&nbsp;</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/_E2wO5NIzC8" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0511/This-GIF-illustrates-global-warming-spiraling-out-of-control">
    <title>This GIF illustrates global warming 'spiraling' out of control </title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0511/This-GIF-illustrates-global-warming-spiraling-out-of-control</link>
    <description><p>Professor Ed Hawkins developed a GIF that illustrates how global climate change has accelerated from 1850 to today.&nbsp;</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/4NOd0H0-1zQ" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0511/Bees-are-in-trouble.-What-s-being-done-to-save-them">
    <title>Bees are in trouble. What's being done to save them?</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0511/Bees-are-in-trouble.-What-s-being-done-to-save-them</link>
    <description><p>An annual survey of US beekeepers paints a bleak picture, with a decline of almost 50 percent in honeybee colonies. New public-private coalitions offer hope.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/RXWb_36qx5Y" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0511/Can-emojis-promote-gender-equality">
    <title>Can emojis promote gender equality? </title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0511/Can-emojis-promote-gender-equality</link>
    <description><p>Four Google employees have proposed adding 13 female professionals to the ranks of emoji characters.&nbsp;</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/esxLlMtBPGU" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0511/How-Canadian-teenager-used-space-archaeology-in-hunt-for-lost-Mayan-city">
    <title>How Canadian teenager used space archaeology in hunt for lost Mayan city</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0511/How-Canadian-teenager-used-space-archaeology-in-hunt-for-lost-Mayan-city</link>
    <description><p>A 15-year-old used star charts and satellite images to hypothesize the location of an undiscovered Mayan city in an example of 'space archaeology.'</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/jrayT1SRI24" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0511/Kepler-has-spotted-1-284-new-exoplanets-thanks-to-new-verification-method">
    <title>Kepler has spotted 1,284 new exoplanets, thanks to new verification method</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0511/Kepler-has-spotted-1-284-new-exoplanets-thanks-to-new-verification-method</link>
    <description><p>Using a new analysis technique, scientists have verified&nbsp;1,284 new exoplanets that were discovered by NASA's Kepler telescope. These additions double the number of planets the telescope has discovered since it was launched in 2009.&nbsp;</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/DCkQsrBUQFw" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0510/Australia-was-home-to-the-world-s-oldest-hatchet-archaeologists-say">
    <title>Australia was home to the world's oldest hatchet, archaeologists say</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0510/Australia-was-home-to-the-world-s-oldest-hatchet-archaeologists-say</link>
    <description><p>Scientists working in Western Australia have unearthed an ancient axe. The scientists dated the artifact to between 46,000 and 49,000 years old, making it the oldest of its kind to be discovered anywhere in the world.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/czgba1xUVTw" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0510/Oxygen-in-Martian-atmosphere-Yes-but-don-t-get-too-excited-yet">
    <title>Oxygen in Martian atmosphere? Yes, but don't get too excited yet.</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0510/Oxygen-in-Martian-atmosphere-Yes-but-don-t-get-too-excited-yet</link>
    <description><p>Detection of atomic oxygen in Mars' upper atmosphere is exciting news for scientists, but not in the way you might think.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/F2_-cIUCd8E" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0510/History-of-human-trade-is-written-in-camel-genes">
    <title>History of human trade is written in camel genes</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0510/History-of-human-trade-is-written-in-camel-genes</link>
    <description><p>A new study finds that one-humped camels' genetic diversity may have been influenced by their role in ancient caravans.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/pwlwwahPBAY" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0510/Why-are-carrots-orange">
    <title>Why are carrots orange?</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0510/Why-are-carrots-orange</link>
    <description><p>Carrots have recently joined the elite ranks of vegetables whose entire genome has been sequenced – revealing&nbsp;the secret behind the vegetable's iconic color.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/XT1I0Zc6AAA" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0510/Pristine-water-ice-spotted-on-Pluto-s-outermost-moon">
    <title>'Pristine' water-ice spotted on Pluto's outermost moon</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0510/Pristine-water-ice-spotted-on-Pluto-s-outermost-moon</link>
    <description><p>New data beamed back from NASA's New Horizons spacecraft confirms that Hydra, Pluto's outermost moon, is largely coated in a remarkably pure water-ice.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/kMCe02AaA04" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0510/Early-Earth-s-air-was-less-than-half-as-thick-as-it-is-today.-Why-does-it-matter">
    <title>Early Earth's air was less than half as thick as it is today. Why does it matter?</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0510/Early-Earth-s-air-was-less-than-half-as-thick-as-it-is-today.-Why-does-it-matter</link>
    <description><p>Scientists thought they had an explanation for the so-called 'faint young sun paradox' in our solar system's early history. But new research could turn that solution on its head.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/bHQcpVtwL8c" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0510/How-an-army-of-oil-eating-bacteria-can-clean-up-the-Gulf">
    <title>How an army of oil-eating bacteria can clean up the Gulf</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0510/How-an-army-of-oil-eating-bacteria-can-clean-up-the-Gulf</link>
    <description><p>In a new study published Monday, a team of researchers say certain bacterial species can use their natural metabolism to efficiently clean up spilled oil.&nbsp;</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/S7Oi_xrNH60" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0509/Pacific-islands-shorelines-disappear-due-to-climate-change">
    <title>Pacific islands, shorelines disappear due to climate change </title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0509/Pacific-islands-shorelines-disappear-due-to-climate-change</link>
    <description><p>A recent study points to the connection between human-caused climate change and some erosion and shoreline recession in a Pacific Island archipelago.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/A9IL8hq-0Bk" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0509/Amazingly-detailed-topographical-map-adds-textured-view-of-Mercury">
    <title>Amazingly detailed topographical map adds textured view of Mercury</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/2016/0509/Amazingly-detailed-topographical-map-adds-textured-view-of-Mercury</link>
    <description><p>Researchers from the US Geological survey combined more than 100,000 images to develop this first-ever topographical map of Mercury.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/2dihrRJWSW0" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
  <item rdf:about="http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/Science-Notebook/2016/0509/Technology-transfer-NASA-opens-vault-of-space-age-patents">
    <title>Technology transfer: NASA opens vault of space-age patents</title>
    <link>http://www.csmonitor.com/Science/Science-Notebook/2016/0509/Technology-transfer-NASA-opens-vault-of-space-age-patents</link>
    <description><p>The space agency has released more than 50 previously patented technologies that could be adopted by innovators to spur America's economy.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/feeds/science/~4/RtqkIJCEkig" height="1" width="1" alt=""/></description>
  </item>
</rdf:RDF>
